---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout
  title="Cups to Millilitres: Baking Conversion Guide"
  description="Convert cups to ml for international baking. Covers US, metric, and imperial cups with a handy chart."
  keywords="cups to ml, baking conversion, cup to millilitres, US cup ml, metric cup, baking measurements, recipe conversion"
>
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <!-- Breadcrumb -->
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-500 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Cooking</span>
      </nav>

      <BlogCrossLinks title="Cups to Millilitres: Baking Conversion Guide" />

      <!-- Article Meta -->
      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2025-06-07">June 7, 2025</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-300 dark:bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>4 min read</span>
      </div>

      <!-- Lead Paragraph -->
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">
        Following a recipe from another country? The "cup" measurement is not universal — a US cup, metric cup, and imperial cup are all different sizes. Here is how to convert accurately for perfect baking results.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: Cup Sizes -->
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-3 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Not All Cups Are Equal</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-6 my-6 not-prose shadow-sm">
        <div class="space-y-2 text-center">
          <p class="text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">1 US cup = 236.6 ml</p>
          <p class="text-sm font-mono text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">1 Metric cup = 250 ml</p>
          <p class="text-sm font-mono text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">1 Imperial cup = 284 ml</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>Most American recipes use US customary cups. Australian and some European recipes use the metric cup (250 ml). The imperial cup is rarely used in modern recipes.</p>

      <!-- Section: Conversion Chart -->
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-3 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Quick Conversion Chart (US Cups)</h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">US Cups</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Millilitres</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Tablespoons</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100 dark:divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
              <td class="px-4 py-3">¼ cup</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">59 ml</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">4 tbsp</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="px-4 py-3">⅓ cup</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">79 ml</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">5⅓ tbsp</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
              <td class="px-4 py-3">½ cup</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">118 ml</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">8 tbsp</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="px-4 py-3">⅔ cup</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">158 ml</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">10⅔ tbsp</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
              <td class="px-4 py-3">¾ cup</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">177 ml</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">12 tbsp</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="px-4 py-3">1 cup</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">237 ml</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">16 tbsp</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
              <td class="px-4 py-3">2 cups</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">473 ml</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center font-mono">32 tbsp</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Tips -->
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-3 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Baking Tips for Metric Conversions</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Liquids:</strong> Use a measuring jug for ml — measuring cups are less precise for liquids</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Flour:</strong> 1 cup of flour ≈ 125g (but varies by how tightly packed)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Sugar:</strong> 1 cup of sugar ≈ 200g (granulated) or 220g (packed brown)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Butter:</strong> 1 cup = 227g = 2 sticks (US)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>When in doubt:</strong> Weigh ingredients in grams for the most accurate baking</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <!-- Section: Why Weight is Better -->
      <h2 class="flex items-center gap-3 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Why Professional Bakers Use Weight</h2>
      <p>Volume measurements (cups) are inconsistent because how you scoop affects the amount. A "cup of flour" can vary by 30% between cooks. That is why professional recipes use grams — it is always exact regardless of technique.</p>

      <!-- Converter CTA -->
      <div class="not-prose mt-10 p-5 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-50 to-orange-50 dark:from-amber-900/20 dark:to-orange-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl shadow-sm">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 flex-wrap">
          <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">
            🔗 Try our free volume converter
          </p>
          <a
            href="/convert/volume"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 hover:bg-amber-600 text-white text-sm font-semibold transition-colors shadow-sm"
          >
            Open Converter →
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Back to Blog -->
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 text-center">
        <a href="/blog" class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-amber-500 transition-colors">
          ← Back to all articles
        </a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
